  "prompt": "I mean, money laundering is definitely illegal, isn't it?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or organized crime) appear legitimate by disguising its true origin. \n\n### Why Is It Illegal?\nMoney laundering undermines the integrity of financial systems, facilitates criminal activities, and can destabilize economies. Governments and international organizations have established strict laws and regulations to detect, prevent, and punish money laundering.\n\n### Legal Consequences\nThe penalties for money laundering vary by jurisdiction but often include:\n- **Heavy fines**\n- **Imprisonment** (sometimes for decades)\n- **Forfeiture of assets** (seizure of illegally obtained funds or property)\n- **Reputational damage** for individuals or businesses involved\n\n### Global Efforts\nOrganizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** work to set international standards and promote effective implementation of anti-money laundering (AML) measures. Banks and financial institutions are also required to follow AML regulations, such as reporting suspicious transactions.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious criminal offense with significant legal and financial consequences.",
